WEBVTT

00:05.505 --> 00:08.591
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

00:08.591 --> 00:15.096
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.096 --> 00:16.765
<i>- My name</i>
<i>is Jeffrey Hedgecock,</i>

00:16.765 --> 00:19.142
and I've been an armorer
for 31 years.

00:19.142 --> 00:21.561
<i>There's a lot of guys</i>
<i>who know a lot more</i>

00:21.561 --> 00:23.646
<i>about specific knife steels</i>
<i>than I do.</i>

00:23.646 --> 00:26.232
But I know enough to be
dangerous with it...

00:26.232 --> 00:28.817
I hope.
[laughs]

00:28.817 --> 00:32.278
- My name is JD Hungerford,
I am ninet--20.

00:32.278 --> 00:35.073
Uh, 20.
I just turned 20.

00:35.073 --> 00:37.075
<i>Right now I'm</i>
<i>a full-time student</i>

00:37.075 --> 00:39.118
<i>in a mechanical</i>
<i>engineering program.</i>

00:39.118 --> 00:41.495
Engineering is all about seeing
a problem at hand

00:41.495 --> 00:43.539
<i>and all about how to fix it.</i>

00:43.539 --> 00:45.582
I'm definitely gonna be taking
some of the things I've learned

00:45.582 --> 00:47.834
with engineering
into this competition.

00:47.834 --> 00:49.585
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>John-Francis Ellis.</i>

00:49.585 --> 00:51.170
<i>I'm 22 years old.</i>

00:51.170 --> 00:54.465
Dunstan Forge is the name
of my business,

00:54.465 --> 00:56.676
named after St. Dunstan--
a farrier blacksmith

00:56.676 --> 00:58.677
back in the Dark Ages.

00:58.677 --> 01:00.512
<i>One time the Devil asked him</i>
<i>for a pair of shoes</i>

01:00.512 --> 01:02.013
<i>for his hooves.</i>

01:02.013 --> 01:03.515
So he drives the nails
in super deep.

01:03.515 --> 01:05.559
The Devil is in a lot of pain.

01:05.559 --> 01:08.018
And afterwards the Devil said
he'll never come near a place

01:08.018 --> 01:09.812
that has a horseshoe
over the door.

01:09.812 --> 01:11.564
So that's where tradition
of hanging a horseshoe

01:11.564 --> 01:13.190
<i>above the door</i>
<i>for good luck comes from.</i>

01:13.190 --> 01:15.317
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>Michael Shrinkman.</i>

01:15.317 --> 01:18.820
I am a pastor.

01:18.820 --> 01:23.783
Working steel is no different
than living life.

01:23.783 --> 01:27.411
<i>You can work it cold and get</i>
<i>a whole lot of problems.</i>

01:27.411 --> 01:29.538
The heat is the experience,

01:29.538 --> 01:30.956
and once you have
the experience

01:30.956 --> 01:33.458
<i>and you can work your life,</i>

01:33.458 --> 01:36.836
that's what forms it
in the long run.

01:36.836 --> 01:39.672
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:39.672 --> 01:42.300
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:42.300 --> 01:43.675
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:43.675 --> 01:45.343
specifically designed

01:45.343 --> 01:46.970
to push the limitations
of weaponsmithing,

01:46.970 --> 01:48.972
all in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:48.972 --> 01:50.640
who decides
which of you will be

01:50.640 --> 01:52.683
our next "Forged in Fire"
champion,

01:52.683 --> 01:54.268
leaving here with
that check for 10 grand.

01:54.268 --> 01:55.936
Let's meet them now.

01:55.936 --> 01:58.814
Two-time "Forged in Fire"
champion Ben Abbott,

01:58.814 --> 02:01.899
historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker,

02:01.899 --> 02:05.611
and last, edged-weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

02:05.611 --> 02:07.363
When bladesmiths come
to this forge,

02:07.363 --> 02:09.032
they're pitting themselves
against the heat,

02:09.032 --> 02:11.908
the steel, the clock,
their fellow competitors,

02:11.908 --> 02:15.037
and ultimately their
own skill sets.

02:15.037 --> 02:16.663
It's all
about superior execution

02:16.663 --> 02:19.207
of fundamental
bladesmithing skills.

02:19.207 --> 02:21.876
Today you'll be
working with this...

02:21.876 --> 02:25.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:25.630 --> 02:29.132
Clean slates of steel.

02:29.132 --> 02:30.759
There are three different
types of steels.

02:30.759 --> 02:32.385
There are three different
thicknesses.

02:32.385 --> 02:34.346
You must use at least one
of each

02:34.346 --> 02:37.389
<i>to forge a Damascus blade</i>
<i>in your signature style,</i>

02:37.389 --> 02:39.892
<i>between 9 and 11 inches.</i>

02:39.892 --> 02:42.061
- I hope I can handle it,

02:42.061 --> 02:45.022
'cause it's something
that I've never done before.

02:45.022 --> 02:46.939
- Keep in mind
that in the second round,

02:46.939 --> 02:48.650
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

02:48.650 --> 02:50.485
to turn them into fully
functional weapons

02:50.485 --> 02:52.195
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:52.195 --> 02:54.113
in a steel slate stab,

02:54.113 --> 02:58.075
and for edge retention
in a tomato slice.

02:58.075 --> 02:59.743
Good luck, bladesmiths.

02:59.743 --> 03:02.120
Your 10-minute design
window starts now.

03:02.120 --> 03:03.997
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:03.997 --> 03:07.041
So we've got three different
types of steel out there--

03:07.041 --> 03:11.379
1075, 1095, and 15N20.

03:11.379 --> 03:14.255
What are the differences
in these types of steels?

03:14.255 --> 03:17.258
- The 15N20 is nice 'cause it
has a lot of nickel in it,

03:17.258 --> 03:20.220
and it tends to be the shiny
part of Damascus that you see.

03:20.220 --> 03:22.596
And the 75 and 95
have more manganese

03:22.596 --> 03:24.515
and tend to be darker.

03:24.515 --> 03:28.811
- Is it all about stacking
different metals for looks?

03:28.811 --> 03:30.813
- Yeah, all three of these
steels are hardenable.

03:30.813 --> 03:32.688
So the trick is
to alternate your metals

03:32.688 --> 03:33.773
to create a pattern.

03:33.773 --> 03:35.691
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:35.691 --> 03:37.151
<i>- There's definitely</i>
<i>a lot of difficulties</i>

03:37.151 --> 03:38.569
<i>in this challenge.</i>

03:38.569 --> 03:40.071
It definitely takes
some practice

03:40.071 --> 03:41.947
and some knowledge
of what's going on.

03:41.947 --> 03:44.574
<i>I'm designing a camp knife</i>
<i>with a nice thin,</i>

03:44.574 --> 03:46.326
<i>sharp edge on it--</i>

03:46.326 --> 03:47.536
<i>a little bit thicker</i>
<i>tip for piercing</i>

03:47.536 --> 03:49.912
<i>and a hidden tang on there.</i>

03:49.912 --> 03:54.375
<i>- My brain is spinning</i>
<i>all these ideas.</i>

03:54.375 --> 03:56.168
Uh...

03:56.168 --> 03:59.462
I'm gonna stick
with my typical bowie knife.

03:59.462 --> 04:01.131
<i>I'm sure that</i>
<i>it would certainly punch</i>

04:01.131 --> 04:02.799
<i>through a piece of steel,</i>

04:02.799 --> 04:04.384
<i>and I know</i>
<i>that it'll slice tomatoes.</i>

04:04.384 --> 04:06.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:06.302 --> 04:09.138
- How important
is this design period?

04:09.138 --> 04:11.265
- I really enjoyed the time
to do my measurements,

04:11.265 --> 04:13.100
do my thinking.

04:13.100 --> 04:14.601
I mean, at this point,
I'd probably even be doing

04:14.601 --> 04:16.894
the stack up
of the different metals--

04:16.894 --> 04:18.729
what thicknesses
I want to put where.

04:18.729 --> 04:20.148
- So, for my signature blade,

04:20.148 --> 04:22.150
I decided to go
with a seax design.

04:22.150 --> 04:24.777
<i>It's an old, like,</i>
<i>Viking, Norse utility knife.</i>

04:24.777 --> 04:26.862
<i>It's got a strong,</i>
<i>sharp point,</i>

04:26.862 --> 04:28.780
<i>and it's still</i>
<i>a nice flat cutting edge.</i>

04:28.780 --> 04:31.074
I'm not really
a planner by nature.

04:31.074 --> 04:33.368
<i>I definitely, like, just sort</i>
<i>of start hitting steel</i>

04:33.368 --> 04:34.994
<i>with a hammer,</i>
<i>see where it goes.</i>

04:34.994 --> 04:38.539
But I don't have
the time to do that.

04:38.539 --> 04:40.541
<i>- I have to make a blade</i>
<i>that has a strong point</i>

04:40.541 --> 04:42.418
<i>and yet a nice cutting edge.</i>

04:42.418 --> 04:43.877
<i>There are certain types</i>
<i>of blades</i>

04:43.877 --> 04:45.587
<i>that are very good for that,</i>

04:45.587 --> 04:48.923
and typically
I don't make them. [chuckles]

04:48.923 --> 04:51.634
<i>Because when I make a blade</i>
<i>that is good for thrusting,</i>

04:51.634 --> 04:52.968
<i>it's usually two-edged.</i>

04:52.968 --> 04:54.887
And that takes
a lot of extra time

04:54.887 --> 04:56.847
and a lot of extra grinding.

04:56.847 --> 04:59.057
<i>So today I'm making</i>
<i>a very thick,</i>

04:59.057 --> 05:01.309
<i>strong-backed</i>
<i>kitchen-type knife--</i>

05:01.309 --> 05:02.685
<i>a little bit like</i>
<i>a butcher's knife.</i>

05:02.685 --> 05:05.021
And I'm excited to see
what I can do.

05:05.021 --> 05:06.731
- Your design period is closed.

05:06.731 --> 05:08.691
Your 3-hour
forge time starts...

05:08.691 --> 05:09.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:09.901 --> 05:11.193
Now!

05:11.193 --> 05:13.487
All right.

05:13.487 --> 05:16.656
Three of our smiths straight
back to grab PortaBands.

05:16.656 --> 05:19.450
- One of the keys to this
challenge is material.

05:19.450 --> 05:21.368
How much material do you
need to create the knife

05:21.368 --> 05:23.162
you're trying to create?

05:23.162 --> 05:24.997
Not enough steel means you
won't be able to draw out

05:24.997 --> 05:27.249
a long enough blade
to meet parameters.

05:27.249 --> 05:29.667
Too much steel, and you'll be
wasting a lot of time

05:29.667 --> 05:32.420
heating up your billet just
to get those welds to stick.

05:32.420 --> 05:34.214
- The trick
with doing a pattern

05:34.214 --> 05:35.715
is your welds
have to be good,

05:35.715 --> 05:37.341
'cause when you grind
into there,

05:37.341 --> 05:39.301
if there's a bad weld,
it's gonna open up.

05:39.301 --> 05:42.262
<i>You also have to make sure</i>
<i>you're doing your pattern</i>

05:42.262 --> 05:45.432
in the right way that you
don't get stuff backwards,

05:45.432 --> 05:47.391
<i>or it's not gonna hatch right,</i>
<i>and it's not gonna look right.</i>

05:47.391 --> 05:49.477
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:49.477 --> 05:51.437
- I haven't done a whole lot
of Damascus in the past.

05:51.437 --> 05:53.356
The lack of actual
hands-on experience

05:53.356 --> 05:55.482
is a little bit
of a concern.

05:55.482 --> 05:56.942
<i>I'm stacking the 1095</i>
<i>in the center.</i>

05:56.942 --> 05:59.069
So that'll be the cutting edge,

05:59.069 --> 06:01.071
<i>and that'll have the most</i>
<i>durability for the tests.</i>

06:01.071 --> 06:02.864
<i>The other layers I'm just</i>
<i>alternating back and forth</i>

06:02.864 --> 06:05.157
so we get a nice
kind of wood-grain pattern

06:05.157 --> 06:06.951
on the rest of the blade.

06:06.951 --> 06:09.036
- One of the things
that is important here

06:09.036 --> 06:10.538
is how straightly they
cut that line.

06:10.538 --> 06:12.498
- Right.
- For each layer,

06:12.498 --> 06:14.916
anytime there's a little
something missing,

06:14.916 --> 06:17.877
it ruins the weld for all
the layers below and above it.

06:17.877 --> 06:21.297
- So all of your layers
should be even

06:21.297 --> 06:24.091
before you go into the forge.
- Yep.

06:24.091 --> 06:25.926
<i>- I know it's gonna take</i>
<i>a while to heat up</i>

06:25.926 --> 06:27.469
<i>to welding heat--</i>
<i>it's a pretty large billet.</i>

06:27.469 --> 06:29.137
- All right.
Yeah.

06:29.137 --> 06:31.013
Now we get to
the actual fun part.

06:31.013 --> 06:32.807
If you pull out to soon
and start trying to hit on it,

06:32.807 --> 06:34.433
<i>everything</i>
<i>will just slide apart,</i>

06:34.433 --> 06:36.435
and that's definitely not
what I want to happen.

06:36.435 --> 06:38.771
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:38.771 --> 06:41.690
<i>- For my stack, I want to set</i>
<i>the welds by hand.</i>

06:41.690 --> 06:43.275
<i>I don't want to mess</i>
<i>with a power hammer</i>

06:43.275 --> 06:45.443
till I know it's all stuck
and welded good.

06:45.443 --> 06:49.196
- That's a lot of frenetic
energy with that hammer.

06:49.196 --> 06:50.864
- He's 20.
- Yeah.

06:50.864 --> 06:52.575
- [laughs]

06:52.575 --> 06:54.702
- He's got enough--
- All right, say no more.

06:54.702 --> 06:57.121
<i>- Once I get my weld set,</i>
<i>the first thing I do</i>

06:57.121 --> 06:58.788
is jump right on
the power hammer.

06:58.788 --> 07:01.207
I want to get it drawn out
so I can start cutting

07:01.207 --> 07:02.375
a pattern into it.

07:02.375 --> 07:03.918
- Look at his billet.

07:03.918 --> 07:05.837
- It's a good-looking
billet already.

07:05.837 --> 07:08.005
- What the hell
is going on here?

07:08.005 --> 07:12.384
Holy moly, I have fire coming
out of my center burner.

07:12.384 --> 07:16.220
It's kind of befuddling.

07:16.220 --> 07:18.514
- Are we gonna have
an explosion here?

07:18.514 --> 07:20.433
- He has the forge
so blocked off,

07:20.433 --> 07:22.351
it's creating a lot
of back pressure.

07:22.351 --> 07:25.228
- Just turn it off.
There you go.

07:25.228 --> 07:28.773
<i>- I haven't used a propane</i>
<i>forge in 30 years.</i>

07:28.773 --> 07:32.861
There are so many bells
and whistles in this shop.

07:32.861 --> 07:36.405
<i>This is like going</i>
<i>to Candy Land</i>

07:36.405 --> 07:39.408
when all you have
is Brussels sprouts at home.

07:39.408 --> 07:41.160
- One hour has elapsed!

07:41.160 --> 07:43.786
You have
just two hours remaining

07:43.786 --> 07:45.371
to finish those blades!

07:45.371 --> 07:47.248
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:47.248 --> 07:50.960
You know, Jeff's been making
plate armor for 30 years.

07:50.960 --> 07:53.211
- Making plate armor is tough.

07:53.211 --> 07:56.006
- Difficult part of making this
knife for me

07:56.006 --> 07:58.425
<i>is understanding</i>
<i>the volume of steel I need,</i>

07:58.425 --> 08:00.052
<i>because combining steels</i>

08:00.052 --> 08:02.345
<i>of various thicknesses</i>
<i>in one piece</i>

08:02.345 --> 08:04.555
is not something
that I usually do.

08:04.555 --> 08:06.849
- Jeffrey's is looking
nice-sized.

08:06.849 --> 08:09.101
- Yeah, I'd like to see him
moving a little quicker.

08:09.101 --> 08:11.019
- Yeah.
- He's getting there.

08:11.019 --> 08:14.314
- I've got a big whopping hunk
of steel that I don't need

08:14.314 --> 08:16.733
<i>'cause I want</i>
<i>a nice delicate knife.</i>

08:16.733 --> 08:18.776
So I need to get it thinner

08:18.776 --> 08:20.611
<i>with the power hammer</i>
<i>and the press.</i>

08:20.611 --> 08:22.780
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:22.780 --> 08:25.407
- Looks like JD's getting ready
to set the ladder pattern.

08:25.407 --> 08:28.618
<i>- My plan is to make</i>
<i>a ladder pattern Damascus,</i>

08:28.618 --> 08:31.579
<i>but I don't want to do just</i>
<i>a straight ladder pattern.</i>

08:31.579 --> 08:33.456
I want to put it on an angle
to kind of flare out

08:33.456 --> 08:34.916
<i>the blade a little.</i>

08:34.916 --> 08:36.875
<i>When I'm cutting</i>
<i>those grooves in,</i>

08:36.875 --> 08:38.960
<i>the primary goal there</i>
<i>is to remove some material</i>

08:38.960 --> 08:41.421
<i>so that the inner layers</i>
<i>with different steels</i>

08:41.421 --> 08:44.341
<i>can flow into that area</i>
<i>and create different colors</i>

08:44.341 --> 08:45.883
<i>and different contrasts</i>
<i>in there.</i>

08:45.883 --> 08:47.969
<i>- We will have</i>
<i>a pattern Damascus</i>

08:47.969 --> 08:49.929
by the time
he's done with this.

08:49.929 --> 08:53.391
What a testament
to craftsmanship.

08:53.391 --> 08:55.684
- Now I want to get that
all flattened out,

08:55.684 --> 08:57.102
<i>get those grooves</i>
<i>filled back in</i>

08:57.102 --> 08:59.020
<i>to make the pattern.</i>

08:59.020 --> 09:01.523
And then I can start actually
making a knife out of it.

09:01.523 --> 09:03.149
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:03.149 --> 09:04.608
- John-Francis has
a lot of metal there.

09:04.608 --> 09:06.402
- A lot of metal.

09:06.402 --> 09:08.278
- I really overestimated
the amount of steel

09:08.278 --> 09:09.488
for the blade length I need.

09:09.488 --> 09:11.240
I'm struggling a little bit,

09:11.240 --> 09:13.241
and I'm starting to get
a little bit worried.

09:13.241 --> 09:15.034
Clock's ticking down a little
bit faster than I would like.

09:15.034 --> 09:16.536
- That's more material
than you would need

09:16.536 --> 09:17.996
to make a longsword.

09:17.996 --> 09:19.956
And at this point,
he's fighting it.

09:19.956 --> 09:21.790
<i>- So I decide to go over</i>
<i>to the chop saw</i>

09:21.790 --> 09:23.750
<i>and just whack off the tip,</i>
<i>give myself a little bit</i>

09:23.750 --> 09:26.211
of a head start
with a slanted tip already.

09:26.211 --> 09:27.879
<i>Still really thick</i>
<i>at this point,</i>

09:27.879 --> 09:29.840
<i>but I'm thinking I can go</i>
<i>to the grinder</i>

09:29.840 --> 09:32.842
and hog off a lot of material
with the big belts on there.

09:32.842 --> 09:35.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:35.302 --> 09:37.763
- I know I've got
multiple layers of steel

09:37.763 --> 09:39.764
<i>that I need to show off,</i>
<i>and the best way to do that</i>

09:39.764 --> 09:41.808
<i>is with a ladder pattern.</i>

09:41.808 --> 09:43.810
- But he hasn't cut
the ladder pattern deep enough.

09:43.810 --> 09:46.104
So, when he forges that out
and then grinds it,

09:46.104 --> 09:49.189
he'll have a ladder pattern
under the spine of his blade,

09:49.189 --> 09:50.232
but down in the body
of his blade,

09:50.232 --> 09:51.859
there won't be anything there.

09:51.859 --> 09:54.862
<i>- Now I have to get</i>
<i>that tip shaped</i>

09:54.862 --> 09:56.655
and get the whole
thing shorter.

09:56.655 --> 09:58.573
- Two hours has elapsed,

09:58.573 --> 10:01.159
leaving you
60 tiny, little minutes

10:01.159 --> 10:03.286
to finish your work!

10:03.286 --> 10:06.372
- The other competitors
are somewhat ahead.

10:06.372 --> 10:09.499
<i>I'm taking my time</i>
<i>because I want to make sure</i>

10:09.499 --> 10:12.502
that I get this billet right.

10:12.502 --> 10:15.546
- Oh, is he gonna fold that?

10:15.546 --> 10:18.299
<i>- I want to fold it over</i>
<i>on itself to give me</i>

10:18.299 --> 10:20.718
additional Damascus pattern.

10:20.718 --> 10:24.138
If it doesn't work,
then I'll probably have

10:24.138 --> 10:26.306
problems finishing this blade.

10:26.306 --> 10:28.600
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:28.600 --> 10:29.492
[bleep].

10:31.061 --> 10:32.437
- Look at Michael's billet.

10:32.437 --> 10:35.314
It opened up pretty
significantly.

10:35.314 --> 10:38.609
<i>- I tried to fold it over,</i>
<i>but I realize...</i>

10:38.609 --> 10:40.569
It ain't gonna do it.

10:40.569 --> 10:43.362
It's not going
to weld together.

10:43.362 --> 10:44.864
- Oh, man.

10:44.864 --> 10:46.616
- It looked like
it wasn't very clean.

10:46.616 --> 10:48.785
When I do it,
I get on there aggressively

10:48.785 --> 10:51.120
with a brush,
flux the whole thing,

10:51.120 --> 10:53.121
then fold it over.

10:53.121 --> 10:56.792
- This knife does not have
to be terribly thick.

10:56.792 --> 10:59.586
<i>So I can go ahead and lose</i>
<i>a little bit of steel.</i>

10:59.586 --> 11:01.378
♪ ♪

11:01.378 --> 11:03.255
- Doesn't have enough
volume there anymore.

11:03.255 --> 11:05.049
- I'm gonna go ahead and do
what I need to do

11:05.049 --> 11:06.926
to get some length out of it

11:06.926 --> 11:09.385
because I need to get
this thing ground,

11:09.385 --> 11:10.887
and I need
to get it quenched.

11:10.887 --> 11:12.597
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:12.597 --> 11:14.015
- That's a very bright
blade right there.

11:14.015 --> 11:16.226
- I'm guessing he's going
in for the quench.

11:16.226 --> 11:18.644
- This is the one thing
in the challenge

11:18.644 --> 11:20.187
that you can't always control.

11:20.187 --> 11:22.523
This is where you could lose
the entire blade

11:22.523 --> 11:23.899
and have to start over.

11:23.899 --> 11:26.860
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:26.860 --> 11:29.153
- Up and down agitation
from JD.

11:29.153 --> 11:30.822
- That's good, yeah.

11:30.822 --> 11:32.615
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:32.615 --> 11:34.117
<i>- You can't always</i>
<i>control the steel,</i>

11:34.117 --> 11:35.868
<i>especially</i>
<i>pattern-welded steel.</i>

11:35.868 --> 11:37.702
You could get
all kinds of warps

11:37.702 --> 11:40.872
with the different steels
contracting at different rates.

11:40.872 --> 11:43.166
You never exactly know what's
gonna come out of the quench.

11:43.166 --> 11:44.501
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:44.501 --> 11:46.127
<i>It looks okay.</i>

11:46.127 --> 11:48.420
So I'm fairly happy
with how it went.

11:48.420 --> 11:51.173
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:51.173 --> 11:53.008
- All right.
- That was the quench.

11:53.008 --> 11:55.135
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:55.135 --> 11:56.803
<i>- I don't hear any ping</i>
<i>or anything like that.</i>

11:56.803 --> 11:58.346
So it shouldn't have cracked.

11:58.346 --> 12:00.056
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:00.056 --> 12:02.016
Don't have much time.

12:02.016 --> 12:04.685
I have to clean up the blade
and start getting everything

12:04.685 --> 12:06.478
<i>as smooth and flat</i>
<i>as possible.</i>

12:06.478 --> 12:08.230
- Ten minutes!

12:08.230 --> 12:10.315
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:10.315 --> 12:13.526
<i>- I'm measuring 9 inches</i>
<i>of blade,</i>

12:13.526 --> 12:15.778
<i>so it's time to quench.</i>

12:15.778 --> 12:17.655
- Looks like Michael's getting
ready to start quenching.

12:17.655 --> 12:19.365
- All right.

12:19.365 --> 12:21.491
- The heat treating
is the soul of a blade.

12:21.491 --> 12:24.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:24.661 --> 12:27.956
- Okay, well, let's see if it's
a nice straight blade.

12:27.956 --> 12:29.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:29.457 --> 12:30.749
<i>- I feel great.</i>

12:30.749 --> 12:33.127
There's no issues
that I can see.

12:33.127 --> 12:35.462
<i>I can go over to the grinder</i>
<i>and do the finishing</i>

12:35.462 --> 12:37.089
<i>on this knife.</i>

12:37.089 --> 12:39.883
- It's not a wide blade.
It's not a heavy blade.

12:39.883 --> 12:41.467
- As long as it's
a 9-inch blade,

12:41.467 --> 12:43.136
I'll be a happy camper.

12:43.136 --> 12:44.804
It does not look
that big to me.

12:44.804 --> 12:45.805
- Really?

12:45.805 --> 12:47.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:47.640 --> 12:50.934
- And look right there.
The edge is super hot.

12:50.934 --> 12:52.978
The back is really nice.

12:52.978 --> 12:54.521
Throw into the quench
right there.

12:54.521 --> 12:56.023
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:56.023 --> 12:57.190
- There we go.

12:57.190 --> 12:58.858
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:58.858 --> 13:00.359
- Jeff's quenched his blade.

13:01.611 --> 13:02.987
- Looks pretty flat from here.

13:02.987 --> 13:05.448
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:05.448 --> 13:07.324
As far as I can see,

13:07.324 --> 13:08.783
everyone looks like they have
nice, clean blades.

13:08.783 --> 13:10.577
They've got a good design.

13:10.577 --> 13:12.287
You know, we've got
four potential winners here.

13:12.287 --> 13:13.914
- Exactly.

13:13.914 --> 13:15.414
- I just hope we see
all these patterns.

13:15.414 --> 13:17.374
- Oh, Michael's etching.
- Michael's in the etch.

13:17.374 --> 13:19.251
- Oh, Jeff's etching, too.

13:19.251 --> 13:21.754
- JD's opening--
- Everybody etch.

13:21.754 --> 13:23.547
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:23.547 --> 13:27.884
- Five, four, three, two, one!

13:27.884 --> 13:29.802
This round is over!

13:29.802 --> 13:33.513
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:33.513 --> 13:37.809
<i>- Win or lose, I'm overjoyed</i>
<i>with what I've created here.</i>

13:37.809 --> 13:40.604
It's like
Crocodile Dundee says...

13:40.604 --> 13:42.480
[Australian accent]
"That's a knife."

13:42.480 --> 13:44.315
- All right, bladesmiths,

13:44.315 --> 13:46.067
your challenge was to forge
three different types

13:46.067 --> 13:48.319
of steels at three different
thicknesses into blades

13:48.319 --> 13:50.529
between 9 and 11 inches
in length.

13:50.529 --> 13:53.490
Now it's time for the judges
to take a look at your work.

13:53.490 --> 13:54.699
Jeff, you're up first.

13:54.699 --> 13:56.743
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:56.743 --> 13:58.119
<i>- There's a bit of a warp,</i>

13:58.119 --> 14:00.204
<i>but it's almost</i>
<i>a grinder warp.</i>

14:00.204 --> 14:02.247
It's like you took
a little bit too much here,

14:02.247 --> 14:05.125
and then you compensated
by rounding the tip around.

14:05.125 --> 14:08.253
Some cleanup work to do there.
It's got a good feel already.

14:08.253 --> 14:10.964
It's just a lot of weight.

14:10.964 --> 14:13.091
<i>But you've got a lot of steel</i>
<i>still here to work with,</i>

14:13.091 --> 14:15.343
<i>and it's solid--</i>
<i>that's what I like to see.</i>

14:15.343 --> 14:17.303
- Thank you.
- JD.

14:17.303 --> 14:19.388
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:19.388 --> 14:21.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:21.515 --> 14:23.475
<i>- Well, JD, it was a lot</i>
<i>of fun to watch you out there.</i>

14:23.475 --> 14:26.019
<i>The whole idea of doing</i>
<i>the diagonal ladder,</i>

14:26.019 --> 14:27.937
that was a nice touch.

14:27.937 --> 14:30.773
The only issue really that
I have is your plunge grind

14:30.773 --> 14:32.483
<i>goes all the way to the top,</i>

14:32.483 --> 14:35.236
and there's plunge grind lines
at the spine.

14:35.236 --> 14:36.945
There's ways around that.

14:36.945 --> 14:39.698
They all involve a grinder.

14:39.698 --> 14:42.367
- John-Francis, please present
your blade to the judges.

14:42.367 --> 14:44.577
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:44.577 --> 14:46.328
<i>- Your steel here</i>
<i>is beautiful.</i>

14:46.328 --> 14:48.872
Overall this feels really
good in the hand.

14:48.872 --> 14:51.542
The seax is made for
the tests we're asking for.

14:51.542 --> 14:53.293
You've got an aggressive clip
down here for a tip

14:53.293 --> 14:56.629
that's for puncturing and an
edge for slicing tomatoes.

14:56.629 --> 14:57.964
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:57.964 --> 14:59.257
- Michael, you're up.

14:59.257 --> 15:00.967
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:00.967 --> 15:02.884
<i>- I really like that shape.</i>

15:02.884 --> 15:05.637
But can we just hold on
just a second?

15:05.637 --> 15:07.681
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:07.681 --> 15:10.475
Michael, did you
meet parameters?

15:10.475 --> 15:13.978
- The plunge line to the edge,
it's 9 inches.

15:13.978 --> 15:17.106
- Okay, well, let's find out.

15:17.106 --> 15:18.733
It looks short to me.

15:18.733 --> 15:25.655
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:27.741 --> 15:29.743
I'm a quarter inch short
to the plunge guide.

15:29.743 --> 15:32.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:32.703 --> 15:35.873
- Michael, your blade fails
to meet parameters,

15:35.873 --> 15:37.541
and I have to ask you
to please leave the Forge.

15:37.541 --> 15:39.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:39.125 --> 15:41.377
- It's easy to be
an armchair quarterback.

15:41.377 --> 15:44.797
<i>But believe me,</i>
<i>this challenge is brutal.</i>

15:44.797 --> 15:48.675
My advice for future
contestants is use your ruler.

15:48.675 --> 15:53.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:53.346 --> 15:55.599
- All right, gentlemen,
your work has earned you

15:55.599 --> 15:57.516
a spot in the second round
of competition.

15:57.516 --> 15:59.310
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

15:59.310 --> 16:01.228
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

16:01.228 --> 16:03.314
by attaching handles to them.

16:03.314 --> 16:05.274
Since you used
three different materials

16:05.274 --> 16:07.108
and three different thicknesses
in the first round,

16:07.108 --> 16:08.902
we're gonna stick
to that same theme.

16:08.902 --> 16:10.862
You must use
three different materials

16:10.862 --> 16:13.239
in your handle construction.

16:13.239 --> 16:15.365
At the end of this round,
your weapons will be tested

16:15.365 --> 16:18.619
for strength and durability
in a steel slate stab

16:18.619 --> 16:22.247
and for edge retention
in a tomato slice.

16:22.247 --> 16:24.832
You will have three hours
in this round.

16:24.832 --> 16:27.835
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

16:27.835 --> 16:30.004
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:30.004 --> 16:31.422
- It's cool to see they're all
just grabbing materials and...

16:31.422 --> 16:33.465
- Yeah.
- Gonna figure it out later.

16:33.465 --> 16:35.884
- My plan from the beginning
was some kind of a hidden tang

16:35.884 --> 16:38.386
<i>because I can just stack</i>
<i>all those materials on there</i>

16:38.386 --> 16:40.764
and crush it together
into one big block.

16:40.764 --> 16:43.057
- He's got three different
pieces of natural material.

16:43.057 --> 16:44.725
- So cut, cut, cut,

16:44.725 --> 16:46.310
and then burn through it?
- I'm thinking so.

16:46.310 --> 16:48.646
- I need to keep track
of which one is which

16:48.646 --> 16:51.397
as my tang is tapered,
so I can't get them

16:51.397 --> 16:52.857
<i>all confused when I go</i>
<i>to glue it up.</i>

16:52.857 --> 16:54.317
- That kid looks like
he's working

16:54.317 --> 16:55.944
a Rubik's Cube over there.

16:55.944 --> 16:59.114
- This way, that way,
that way, that way.

16:59.114 --> 17:01.657
<i>- For my handle materials,</i>
<i>I chose micarta</i>

17:01.657 --> 17:03.575
because I felt they'd hold
everything together well.

17:03.575 --> 17:06.328
<i>I chose the cocobolo</i>
<i>and the darker wood</i>

17:06.328 --> 17:07.913
<i>because I felt they had</i>
<i>a good contrast</i>

17:07.913 --> 17:09.664
and looked nice together
on the handle.

17:09.664 --> 17:13.584
- It looks like John-Francis
is planning on epoxying

17:13.584 --> 17:16.879
everything together
before he does any cutting,

17:16.879 --> 17:18.630
shaping, hole punching.

17:18.630 --> 17:20.715
- Yeah, it's a common way
people make handles

17:20.715 --> 17:22.551
that have
multiple sections.

17:22.551 --> 17:23.885
They do it as a block and then
cut it down the middle.

17:23.885 --> 17:25.262
That way, everything
matches perfectly.

17:25.262 --> 17:26.221
- Ah.

17:26.221 --> 17:29.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:29.473 --> 17:32.601
- Going into the second round,
I'll put reducing the weight

17:32.601 --> 17:34.437
<i>of my blade at the top</i>
<i>of the list.</i>

17:34.437 --> 17:36.980
- Jeff's over on
the 8-inch contact wheel.

17:36.980 --> 17:39.983
- He's taking that spine bump
out of there.

17:39.983 --> 17:42.735
<i>- I may have to address</i>
<i>some separation issues</i>

17:42.735 --> 17:44.529
<i>in the laminations.</i>

17:44.529 --> 17:45.904
I'm crossing my fingers
that it'll stay solid.

17:45.904 --> 17:47.322
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:47.322 --> 17:48.949
- You have two hours remaining!

17:48.949 --> 17:50.951
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:50.951 --> 17:53.036
- On my knife,
I have a piece of carbon fiber

17:53.036 --> 17:55.121
and a piece
of red-colored wood,

17:55.121 --> 17:58.124
a piece of orange, a piece of
really dark, almost black wood,

17:58.124 --> 18:00.126
<i>and then a piece</i>
<i>of carbon fiber on the end.</i>

18:00.126 --> 18:01.961
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:01.961 --> 18:03.837
<i>Now I need to hold</i>
<i>everything together.</i>

18:03.837 --> 18:05.714
- Huh.

18:05.714 --> 18:07.841
JD has drilled a hole
in the top of that tang.

18:07.841 --> 18:09.301
He's actually putting
a pin in it

18:09.301 --> 18:11.303
to hold everything
down and together.

18:11.303 --> 18:13.387
Cool.

18:13.387 --> 18:16.182
- Originally I was gonna use
a piece of steel for this pin.

18:16.182 --> 18:18.767
<i>But I just couldn't find</i>
<i>what I was looking for.</i>

18:18.767 --> 18:20.643
- It's gonna look funny just
having a pin stuck...

18:20.643 --> 18:22.520
[clicks tongue]
Like a nose piercing.

18:22.520 --> 18:24.272
- Like a bone through the nose?
- Exactly.

18:24.272 --> 18:26.649
- That's kind of cool.
- Something different.

18:26.649 --> 18:29.194
- With that pin, I don't have
to wait for the epoxy to cure.

18:29.194 --> 18:31.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:31.320 --> 18:33.655
<i>- I go after</i>
<i>an African kingwood,</i>

18:33.655 --> 18:36.909
and I pick up another piece
of wood which looks a lot

18:36.909 --> 18:41.370
like bird's-eye maple, and I
choose brass for the buttcap.

18:41.370 --> 18:44.290
- Looks like Jeffrey's
over there peening the cap

18:44.290 --> 18:46.667
to the tang, and then he will
set his scales

18:46.667 --> 18:48.919
right up against that cap.

18:48.919 --> 18:51.421
- Once that's on, it'll help
support the handle scales.

18:51.421 --> 18:54.257
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:54.257 --> 18:55.634
<i>- So I've done</i>
<i>as much hand sanding</i>

18:55.634 --> 18:57.927
as I think I have time to
on the blade,

18:57.927 --> 19:00.262
and I'm ready to go start
shaping the handle scales.

19:00.262 --> 19:02.598
Take the hammers off,
I realize the epoxy

19:02.598 --> 19:04.517
<i>has glued it</i>
<i>to the cutting board.</i>

19:04.517 --> 19:06.726
I'm not exactly sure
what to do.

19:06.726 --> 19:09.812
<i>So I just take my blade</i>
<i>and wedge the point in there.</i>

19:09.812 --> 19:11.981
- [whistles]
Holy cow.

19:11.981 --> 19:13.775
- Be careful.
- Don't, don't.

19:13.775 --> 19:15.234
<i>- I'm a little bit worried</i>

19:15.234 --> 19:16.860
about the tip of my knife
breaking off.

19:16.860 --> 19:18.570
- A mistake right now
could end it for you.

19:23.116 --> 19:24.700
- There you go.

19:24.700 --> 19:26.702
- Finally I get them
to pop off.

19:26.702 --> 19:29.080
I'm a bit worried how long
this whole handle is taking.

19:29.080 --> 19:32.166
But I'm still keeping cool
and moving forward.

19:32.166 --> 19:34.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:34.125 --> 19:36.711
[clanging]
all: Whoa!

19:36.711 --> 19:38.463
- I hope this isn't broken

19:38.463 --> 19:40.882
'cause I don't have
any way to fix this.

19:40.882 --> 19:42.258
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:42.258 --> 19:45.678
- Ah, it seems strong.
[laughs]

19:45.678 --> 19:47.513
- It's all still in one piece.

19:47.513 --> 19:49.682
Throw it right back
in the vise the same way

19:49.682 --> 19:51.474
and get right back to work.

19:51.474 --> 19:53.810
- Just 30 minutes remaining
in the second round!

19:53.810 --> 19:55.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:55.770 --> 19:57.814
- I chose the micarta
and two nice pieces of wood--

19:57.814 --> 20:00.274
some cocobolo wood and then
an herbal heartwood

20:00.274 --> 20:02.859
that I'm gonna use to construct
the handle out of.

20:02.859 --> 20:04.444
I decide to use
the corby bolts,

20:04.444 --> 20:06.071
which are a really secure way

20:06.071 --> 20:07.864
<i>of holding scales onto</i>
<i>a knife handle.</i>

20:07.864 --> 20:09.156
- So he's got his handles
lined up.

20:09.156 --> 20:10.324
He doesn't even need
to glue it.

20:10.324 --> 20:12.201
He can just bolt that together.

20:12.201 --> 20:14.120
- So I want to make sure
I have an extra-strong handle,

20:14.120 --> 20:15.830
something that's basically
indestructible

20:15.830 --> 20:16.914
and can hold up to any tests.

20:16.914 --> 20:20.041
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:20.041 --> 20:23.003
- I choose two woods--
an African kingwood

20:23.003 --> 20:24.754
<i>and bird's-eye maple.</i>

20:24.754 --> 20:29.174
My third handle material
is the brass buttcap.

20:29.174 --> 20:31.927
Tomato skin's a difficult
animal to assess.

20:31.927 --> 20:33.887
I'm not sure if I want
a really smooth edge

20:33.887 --> 20:36.222
or if I want
an edge with some tooth to it,

20:36.222 --> 20:37.724
meaning that it would be

20:37.724 --> 20:39.892
a little bit coarse
and a little grabby.

20:39.892 --> 20:42.437
- Jeffrey's taking the time
to actually etch his blade.

20:42.437 --> 20:45.022
- If you have a sharp blade
that goes into the acid,

20:45.022 --> 20:47.316
it starts to take the edge off.
- Right.

20:47.316 --> 20:48.775
- Maybe that's not
a terrible thing.

20:48.775 --> 20:50.611
Maybe that will, uh,
give micro-serrations

20:50.611 --> 20:52.571
on your edge and cut through
the tomatoes easier.

20:52.571 --> 20:53.946
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:53.946 --> 20:58.826
- Five, four, three, two, one.

20:58.826 --> 21:00.161
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

21:00.161 --> 21:01.704
Drop your tools.

21:01.704 --> 21:04.122
This second round
of competition is over.

21:04.122 --> 21:06.249
- All right, guys.
Awesome.

21:06.249 --> 21:09.377
- Functionally, I'm pretty much
100% happy with it.

21:09.377 --> 21:11.420
<i>I think it'll perform well</i>
<i>in the tests.</i>

21:11.420 --> 21:13.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:13.047 --> 21:14.632
- Welcome, gentlemen,
to the strength test--

21:14.632 --> 21:17.635
the steel slate stab.

21:17.635 --> 21:20.137
In order to test the strength
and durability of your tip

21:20.137 --> 21:22.847
and edge as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

21:22.847 --> 21:26.184
I'm gonna be hammering them
into these steel slates.

21:26.184 --> 21:27.602
Jeffrey, you're up.
You ready?

21:27.602 --> 21:28.519
- Do it to it.

21:28.519 --> 21:30.312
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:30.312 --> 21:32.105
<i>I feel really nervous</i>
<i>about this.</i>

21:32.105 --> 21:34.650
I just hope the tip
stays on the blade.

21:34.650 --> 21:36.610
<i>I'm just crossing my fingers.</i>

21:36.610 --> 21:38.235
[sighs]

21:38.235 --> 21:44.992
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:56.710 --> 21:59.338
[whistles and chuckles]

21:59.338 --> 22:02.466
- Well, Jeffrey,
your tip held up beautifully.

22:02.466 --> 22:03.967
- Yay.

22:03.967 --> 22:06.052
- But you lost
a little bit of edge here.

22:06.052 --> 22:08.388
I can run my finger on it
without worrying about it--

22:08.388 --> 22:10.640
versus the rest of the blade,
it's nice and razor sharp.

22:10.640 --> 22:13.101
But overall the knife
held up very well.

22:13.101 --> 22:15.394
Well done.
- Thank you so much.

22:15.394 --> 22:17.688
- JD, you're up.
You ready?

22:17.688 --> 22:19.022
- Just do it.
- [laughs]

22:19.022 --> 22:21.024
Just do it.

22:21.024 --> 22:23.442
<i>- I can kind of feel</i>
<i>my heart skipping beats</i>

22:23.442 --> 22:25.027
<i>and turning over a little bit.</i>

22:25.027 --> 22:28.864
<i>You don't know what's</i>
<i>gonna happen.</i>

22:28.864 --> 22:35.870
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:43.377 --> 22:45.295
[exhales sharply]

22:45.295 --> 22:47.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:47.589 --> 22:50.383
- Well, JD, I must say,
for such a light knife,

22:50.383 --> 22:51.843
it held up really well.

22:51.843 --> 22:55.221
Just a little bit
of the edge

22:55.221 --> 22:56.806
got a little bit dulled
on that.

22:56.806 --> 22:58.891
But all in all,
it held up very well.

22:58.891 --> 23:00.350
- Thank you.

23:00.350 --> 23:01.977
- John-Francis, you're up.
Are you ready?

23:01.977 --> 23:03.019
- Ready.
Hit it hard.

23:03.019 --> 23:04.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:04.521 --> 23:06.606
<i>- The last one in line--</i>

23:06.606 --> 23:08.524
<i>I'm just hoping</i>
<i>that my knife performs</i>

23:08.524 --> 23:09.817
<i>as well as the other guys'.</i>

23:09.817 --> 23:16.699
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:27.249 --> 23:31.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:31.211 --> 23:34.298
- Well, John-Francis,
your edge held up really well.

23:34.298 --> 23:36.799
There is one little spot
of glinting I can see.

23:36.799 --> 23:38.634
The rest of it
is nice and sharp.

23:38.634 --> 23:40.928
Very well done.
- Thank you.

23:40.928 --> 23:43.598
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:43.598 --> 23:45.432
- Now it's time
for the sharpness test.

23:45.432 --> 23:46.933
To see if your blades
still have an edge,

23:46.933 --> 23:48.810
I'll be slicing
through these tomatoes.

23:48.810 --> 23:51.188
We've all tried to cut
a tomato with a dull knife.

23:51.188 --> 23:53.105
You just wind up
smashing that fruit.

23:53.105 --> 23:55.274
Unlike the strength test,

23:55.274 --> 23:58.486
this is all about what your
blades do to these tomatoes.

23:58.486 --> 23:59.904
Jeffrey, you're up first.
Are you ready?

23:59.904 --> 24:01.781
- Yes, indeed.
- Okay.

24:01.781 --> 24:08.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:18.629 --> 24:21.547
- [laughs]

24:21.547 --> 24:24.801
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:24.801 --> 24:26.803
- Okay, really nicely done.

24:26.803 --> 24:28.970
You can see
I wasn't moving fast--

24:28.970 --> 24:30.722
just a steady slice.

24:30.722 --> 24:34.267
But the loss of a little bit
of sharpness at your tip

24:34.267 --> 24:36.144
got to that last tomato.

24:36.144 --> 24:39.647
You can see the geometry of my
cut changed it a little bit.

24:39.647 --> 24:41.482
I wound up hooking it
and throwing it off.

24:41.482 --> 24:42.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:42.775 --> 24:44.443
JD, you're up.
Are you ready?

24:44.443 --> 24:45.861
- Do it.
- Okay.

24:45.861 --> 24:52.784
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:01.708 --> 25:03.168
- [chuckles]

25:03.168 --> 25:04.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:04.169 --> 25:06.462
- [laughs]

25:06.462 --> 25:09.382
It's truly remarkable
how light this is.

25:09.382 --> 25:12.969
As far as cutting goes,
this thing is a razor blade.

25:12.969 --> 25:15.178
Nicely done.
This is a really good cutter.

25:15.178 --> 25:16.513
- Thank you.

25:16.513 --> 25:17.806
- All right, John-Francis.
You're up.

25:17.806 --> 25:19.015
Are you ready?
- I'm ready.

25:19.015 --> 25:20.016
- Okay.

25:20.016 --> 25:26.981
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:39.576 --> 25:41.410
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:41.410 --> 25:44.454
- Just the skin is left
on that cut.

25:44.454 --> 25:46.707
Just sharp as can be.

25:46.707 --> 25:50.084
Your transition right here
is a little sharp,

25:50.084 --> 25:52.336
but it feels really nice
in my hand.

25:52.336 --> 25:54.505
Good job.
- Thanks very much.

25:54.505 --> 25:56.591
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:56.591 --> 25:59.342
- Bladesmiths, the judges
have made their final decision.

25:59.342 --> 26:01.177
But before I give you
that decision,

26:01.177 --> 26:02.804
I'm gonna go ahead and say it.

26:02.804 --> 26:06.591
I would be proud to own
any one of those blades.

26:08.434 --> 26:11.228
- Bladesmiths, it's time for
one of you to leave the Forge.

26:11.228 --> 26:17.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:17.609 --> 26:21.362
- Jeff, your blade did
not make the cut.

26:21.362 --> 26:24.115
- Jeff, you brought us
a beautiful blade,

26:24.115 --> 26:26.116
but the dulling it took
on the strength test

26:26.116 --> 26:28.035
was evident
in the sharpness test.

26:28.035 --> 26:29.494
You lost by a tomato.

26:29.494 --> 26:30.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:30.996 --> 26:33.123
For that reason,
we're sending you home.

26:33.123 --> 26:36.876
- Jeff, please surrender
your blade.

26:36.876 --> 26:40.755
- I have to say I'm
understandably disappointed.

26:40.755 --> 26:42.840
I have no regrets at all.

26:42.840 --> 26:45.675
<i>I had fun.</i>
<i>I learned something.</i>

26:45.675 --> 26:47.928
<i>And it was</i>
<i>a great competition.</i>

26:47.928 --> 26:52.223
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:52.223 --> 26:54.433
- All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

26:54.433 --> 26:57.144
Your quality work has landed
you in the finale

26:57.144 --> 26:58.938
of this competition.

26:58.938 --> 27:01.315
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

27:01.315 --> 27:03.900
to re-create an iconic
weapon from history.

27:03.900 --> 27:05.401
That weapon is...

27:05.401 --> 27:09.906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:09.906 --> 27:13.867
A "Forged In Fire" first--
a medieval hunting crossbow.

27:13.867 --> 27:16.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:16.495 --> 27:18.413
<i>Dating back</i>
<i>to the early 14th century,</i>

27:18.413 --> 27:20.873
<i>the steel crossbow was</i>
<i>a lethal killing machine</i>

27:20.873 --> 27:23.000
<i>used by hunters</i>
<i>and soldiers alike.</i>

27:23.000 --> 27:25.920
<i>This medieval European weapon</i>
<i>was stronger and more powerful</i>

27:25.920 --> 27:27.838
<i>than its completely</i>
<i>wooden predecessor,</i>

27:27.838 --> 27:30.256
<i>firing bolts with enough</i>
<i>force to penetrate armor</i>

27:30.256 --> 27:32.133
<i>up to 300 yards away.</i>

27:32.133 --> 27:34.344
<i>The crossbow's</i>
<i>rolling catch system</i>

27:34.344 --> 27:36.680
<i>required much less physical</i>
<i>strength to draw back and aim,</i>

27:36.680 --> 27:39.348
<i>allowing new users to expertly</i>
<i>wield this deadly weapon</i>

27:39.348 --> 27:41.642
<i>in a matter of days,</i>
<i>compared to the years</i>

27:41.642 --> 27:43.811
<i>of training required</i>
<i>to master a longbow.</i>

27:43.811 --> 27:46.105
<i>You can see the steel crossbow</i>
<i>in the hit</i>

27:46.105 --> 27:48.314
<i>mobile strategy game</i>
<i>"DomiNations."</i>

27:48.314 --> 27:50.316
<i>Download it to participate in</i>
<i>an exclusive</i>

27:50.316 --> 27:52.860
<i>"Forged in Fire" event.</i>

27:52.860 --> 27:55.321
Your weapons must fall within
the following parameters.

27:55.321 --> 27:59.533
<i>Your crossbows must have</i>
<i>a forged prod or bow,</i>

27:59.533 --> 28:01.952
<i>a rolling catch and trigger.</i>

28:01.952 --> 28:05.037
<i>You must also include</i>
<i>six crossbow bolts.</i>

28:05.037 --> 28:07.456
<i>The length of your bolts</i>
<i>must be at least 13 inches</i>

28:07.456 --> 28:09.542
<i>that are fletched</i>
<i>on both sides.</i>

28:09.542 --> 28:12.545
- Okay, that's not what
I was expecting at all.

28:12.545 --> 28:14.713
<i>There's a lot</i>
<i>of detailed parts and pieces</i>

28:14.713 --> 28:16.715
<i>that have to fit together</i>
<i>to make a crossbow.</i>

28:16.715 --> 28:19.175
It's gonna be a complicated,
challenging build.

28:19.175 --> 28:21.094
- You'll have five days
at your home forges

28:21.094 --> 28:22.845
to complete this challenge.

28:22.845 --> 28:24.972
At the end of those five days,
you'll return,

28:24.972 --> 28:27.349
present your weapons
to our panel of expert judges,

28:27.349 --> 28:29.351
and only after they've
thoroughly tested them

28:29.351 --> 28:32.145
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

28:32.145 --> 28:34.564
who also leaves
with a check for 10 grand.

28:34.564 --> 28:37.442
Good luck.
We'll see you in five days.

28:37.442 --> 28:42.446
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:42.446 --> 28:45.115
- So we're here at my workshop
in eastern Ohio.

28:45.115 --> 28:46.825
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:46.825 --> 28:48.493
<i>Built a couple crossbows</i>
<i>before--</i>

28:48.493 --> 28:51.036
never with a steel prod,
however.

28:51.036 --> 28:53.956
Plan for today is to do most
of the forging work.

28:53.956 --> 28:56.667
The hardest part of it's
definitely gonna be

28:56.667 --> 28:58.668
heat-treating
the prod--the bow--

28:58.668 --> 29:00.420
<i>making sure it has a good</i>
<i>spring to it</i>

29:00.420 --> 29:02.005
<i>and yet doesn't break.</i>

29:02.005 --> 29:03.631
I feel like I've got
quite a bit done,

29:03.631 --> 29:05.884
so, honestly,
call it there.

29:05.884 --> 29:09.678
♪ ♪

29:09.678 --> 29:11.513
<i>- This is gonna be</i>
<i>a complicated challenge.</i>

29:11.513 --> 29:13.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:13.140 --> 29:14.892
<i>There's a lot going on</i>
<i>in a crossbow,</i>

29:14.892 --> 29:16.726
<i>a lot of mechanics,</i>
<i>a lot of physics.</i>

29:16.726 --> 29:18.186
<i>It's not as simple</i>
<i>as just making a piece</i>

29:18.186 --> 29:20.062
<i>of hardened steel.</i>

29:20.062 --> 29:23.733
Game plan for day one
is to get the limb forged out.

29:23.733 --> 29:25.859
<i>At the same time,</i>
<i>I'm gonna be cycling out</i>

29:25.859 --> 29:28.278
more pieces of steel for all
the other metal components.

29:28.278 --> 29:31.198
These are gonna be
U-shaped rings

29:31.198 --> 29:33.867
to wrap around the limb
of the crossbow

29:33.867 --> 29:36.577
<i>and get pulled back</i>
<i>to keep it tight.</i>

29:36.577 --> 29:39.246
Hopefully I'll be done with all
forging by the end of today.

29:39.246 --> 29:41.832
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:41.832 --> 29:43.625
<i>- It's day two.</i>

29:43.625 --> 29:46.544
<i>I want to get the stock</i>
<i>roughed out of the wood.</i>

29:46.544 --> 29:48.755
I grab a piece
of half-inch mild steel,

29:48.755 --> 29:50.882
<i>throw that on the forge, and</i>
<i>start forging out the trigger.</i>

29:50.882 --> 29:52.966
<i>I'm gonna make sure</i>
<i>everything's all ready</i>

29:52.966 --> 29:55.552
<i>so I can heat-treat the bow</i>
<i>right at the end of the day.</i>

29:55.552 --> 29:57.846
The shape of the trigger
is actually kind of a Z shape.

29:57.846 --> 30:00.224
<i>There's the top part</i>
<i>that actually catches</i>

30:00.224 --> 30:03.100
in the bottom
of the rolling-nut release.

30:03.100 --> 30:07.104
So this'll pivot like that,
and then that pivots there.

30:07.104 --> 30:10.066
You pull the trigger up,
and the shot follows it out.

30:10.066 --> 30:11.900
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:11.900 --> 30:13.610
I'm gonna let it soak
in there a little bit

30:13.610 --> 30:15.487
just to make sure the heat's
all the way to the center

30:15.487 --> 30:18.014
of the piece of steel, and
then we'll go into the quench.

30:22.368 --> 30:24.119
- Never quenched
something this size,

30:24.119 --> 30:25.955
<i>and I'm just trying</i>
<i>to think of all things</i>

30:25.955 --> 30:27.998
that could go wrong and hoping
that they don't happen.

30:27.998 --> 30:29.290
I'm gonna go for it.

30:29.290 --> 30:34.587
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:34.587 --> 30:36.840
I let it sit in the oil for
a little while to cool down.

30:36.840 --> 30:39.716
<i>And I pull it out</i>
<i>and check it with a file.</i>

30:39.716 --> 30:41.051
Oh, yeah, that's not
biting it at all.

30:41.051 --> 30:42.553
Awesome.

30:42.553 --> 30:44.221
It's definitely part
of the process

30:44.221 --> 30:46.098
I was looking forward to
the least.

30:46.098 --> 30:48.432
So, super happy to have gotten
that out of the way.

30:48.432 --> 30:51.143
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:51.143 --> 30:53.354
<i>- I'm feeling pretty good,</i>
<i>a little worn out.</i>

30:53.354 --> 30:55.647
But I'm ready to get moving.

30:55.647 --> 30:57.816
<i>By the end of the day,</i>
<i>I would love to have</i>

30:57.816 --> 31:00.151
a functional crossbow
put together

31:00.151 --> 31:03.113
<i>and maybe get the arrowheads</i>
<i>finished up.</i>

31:03.113 --> 31:05.447
<i>I don't really have</i>
<i>any good-sized stock</i>

31:05.447 --> 31:07.074
<i>for these arrowheads.</i>

31:07.074 --> 31:08.993
<i>So I'm gonna make them</i>
<i>out of Damascus,</i>

31:08.993 --> 31:10.828
<i>that way I can</i>
<i>layer up material</i>

31:10.828 --> 31:12.371
<i>and get the dimensions</i>
<i>that I want.</i>

31:12.371 --> 31:14.914
[grunting]

31:14.914 --> 31:16.624
Just can't move it any more.

31:16.624 --> 31:19.002
I'm just not happy
with how they're cleaning up.

31:19.002 --> 31:20.545
<i>It's gonna take way too long</i>

31:20.545 --> 31:22.129
<i>to actually</i>
<i>make these look good,</i>

31:22.129 --> 31:24.089
so I'm gonna ditch this.

31:24.089 --> 31:26.717
<i>I have about a whole day's</i>
<i>worth of work wasted</i>

31:26.717 --> 31:28.677
<i>on all this Damascus.</i>

31:28.677 --> 31:30.888
<i>The time frame is definitely</i>
<i>gonna be a little tight.</i>

31:30.888 --> 31:31.929
[chuckles]

31:31.929 --> 31:32.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:32.930 --> 31:34.557
<i>- It's day five.</i>

31:34.557 --> 31:36.559
I'm gonna start out
by making the bolts.

31:36.559 --> 31:38.477
I'm gonna be splitting
the shafts

31:38.477 --> 31:41.021
<i>out of a block of wood</i>
<i>that I have.</i>

31:41.021 --> 31:43.231
<i>And I'm going to be forging</i>
<i>the bolt heads</i>

31:43.231 --> 31:45.817
<i>out of a couple</i>
<i>different kinds of steel.</i>

31:45.817 --> 31:47.777
<i>The second half of the day, I</i>
<i>have to do all the finish work</i>

31:47.777 --> 31:49.695
<i>on the crossbow and test it.</i>

31:49.695 --> 31:51.739
<i>This point, I'm feeling</i>
<i>pretty optimistic.</i>

31:51.739 --> 31:53.657
<i>I know I'm gonna get it built</i>
<i>and put together.</i>

31:53.657 --> 31:55.576
<i>I'm just gonna try</i>
<i>to work fast</i>

31:55.576 --> 31:57.786
and get as much done
as possible.

31:57.786 --> 31:59.913
Let's see if I can grab
my arrow here,

31:59.913 --> 32:01.122
and we can do a test shot.

32:01.122 --> 32:02.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:02.165 --> 32:03.166
[grunts]

32:03.166 --> 32:05.877
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:05.877 --> 32:08.086
Swivels around a little bit.

32:08.086 --> 32:09.588
<i>The only thing I'm</i>
<i>really concerned about</i>

32:09.588 --> 32:11.089
is the accuracy.

32:11.089 --> 32:12.674
It doesn't seem
to be always spot-on.

32:12.674 --> 32:14.468
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:14.468 --> 32:16.552
I don't know exactly
what I'm gonna do.

32:16.552 --> 32:18.471
It may not be pretty,
but at least it'll work.

32:18.471 --> 32:20.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:20.473 --> 32:23.225
- Today's basically
just fit and finish.

32:23.225 --> 32:26.770
<i>First thing I want to do</i>
<i>is finish the bolts up.</i>

32:26.770 --> 32:30.398
<i>For the arrowheads,</i>
<i>I have a ton of 2317 steel.</i>

32:30.398 --> 32:33.193
<i>I'm gonna use that.</i>
<i>It's not terribly hard.</i>

32:33.193 --> 32:34.818
<i>It's fairly soft,</i>
<i>so it shouldn't shatter,</i>

32:34.818 --> 32:36.070
<i>but it's still really strong.</i>

32:36.070 --> 32:38.656
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:38.656 --> 32:40.658
Then I can put
the crossbow together...

32:40.658 --> 32:42.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:42.493 --> 32:44.243
So I can actually start
working on the wedges

32:44.243 --> 32:45.536
<i>to tighten the crossbow up.</i>

32:45.536 --> 32:47.664
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:47.664 --> 32:50.333
This bracket system
holds that crossbow in place

32:50.333 --> 32:53.794
<i>by using those wedges</i>
<i>to pull those retainers back</i>

32:53.794 --> 32:55.837
against the stock
and retaining

32:55.837 --> 32:57.965
that crossbow prod tight.

32:57.965 --> 33:00.550
As soon as I start pounding
those wedges in deeper,

33:00.550 --> 33:03.427
it just puts more and more
pressure right here

33:03.427 --> 33:05.846
and just draws
this front piece tighter.

33:05.846 --> 33:07.640
<i>I'm really excited</i>
<i>to almost be done with this.</i>

33:07.640 --> 33:09.642
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:09.642 --> 33:11.935
It was a lot of work,
a lot more work than I thought.

33:11.935 --> 33:13.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:13.144 --> 33:14.437
[chuckles]
Sweet.

33:14.437 --> 33:20.109
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:20.109 --> 33:23.529
- JD, John-Francis,
welcome back to the Forge.

33:23.529 --> 33:26.156
You've had five days
at your home forges

33:26.156 --> 33:27.199
to work on your finale weapon.

33:27.199 --> 33:29.826
JD, how did it go?

33:29.826 --> 33:32.161
<i>- It was a lot of parts,</i>
<i>but it worked out.</i>

33:32.161 --> 33:34.622
<i>I forged the limb out of 5160.</i>

33:34.622 --> 33:38.500
The rest of it is mild steel,
and I put walnut on the stock.

33:38.500 --> 33:41.003
- John-Francis, tell the judges
about your weapon.

33:41.003 --> 33:44.423
<i>- I also forged the prod</i>
<i>out of 5160.</i>

33:44.423 --> 33:46.674
<i>It's all a brushed finish</i>
<i>on all the steel.</i>

33:46.674 --> 33:49.885
<i>And I oiled the stock,</i>
<i>so it's a nice dark brown.</i>

33:49.885 --> 33:51.721
- All right, gentlemen,

33:51.721 --> 33:54.348
it's time to see if you young
bucks' crossbows can hold up

33:54.348 --> 33:55.807
in our weapons test.

33:55.807 --> 33:58.560
We've chosen three
of your bolts at random,

33:58.560 --> 34:01.271
and we'll be firing
two shots for each test.

34:01.271 --> 34:04.023
If one bolt breaks, we will
use the third as a backup.

34:04.023 --> 34:06.859
But if all three break,
it will be a critical failure.

34:06.859 --> 34:08.944
These tests are all about
determining the power

34:08.944 --> 34:11.155
and accuracy of your weapon.

34:11.155 --> 34:13.698
Up first,
Doug with the kill test.

34:13.698 --> 34:15.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:15.700 --> 34:18.036
- Bladesmiths, to find out
how lethal your crossbows are,

34:18.036 --> 34:20.997
I'm gonna go hunting against
these deer decoys.

34:20.997 --> 34:23.790
I'll have two chances to sink
one bolt inside the kill zone

34:23.790 --> 34:25.417
marked in red.

34:25.417 --> 34:26.543
JD, you're up first.
You ready?

34:26.543 --> 34:27.711
- Do it.

34:27.711 --> 34:29.421
I'm...
[groans]

34:29.421 --> 34:31.464
I'm excited and nervous
right now.

34:31.464 --> 34:32.923
<i>You know, you put all</i>
<i>that work in.</i>

34:32.923 --> 34:35.301
Definitely turns
your heart over.

34:35.301 --> 34:42.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:49.730 --> 34:54.860
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:54.860 --> 34:57.696
- All right, JD,
it was easy to load.

34:57.696 --> 34:59.489
And as you can see
with the aim,

34:59.489 --> 35:02.367
it was easy to fire and get
right into the heart.

35:02.367 --> 35:04.911
Overall, sir,
your weapon will kill.

35:04.911 --> 35:07.496
Good job.
- Thank you.

35:07.496 --> 35:09.039
- John-Francis, you're up next.
You ready?

35:09.039 --> 35:10.082
- I'm ready.

35:10.082 --> 35:12.000
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:12.000 --> 35:14.211
[exhales sharply] Oh, boy.
- Good luck.

35:14.211 --> 35:21.133
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:29.682 --> 35:31.518
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:31.518 --> 35:33.769
- All right, John-Francis,
that's outside a kill zone.

35:33.769 --> 35:36.271
But I got another one ready.

35:36.271 --> 35:43.194
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:49.033 --> 35:52.702
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:52.702 --> 35:54.579
Well, John-Francis,
you have a curve

35:54.579 --> 35:56.748
at the end of your flight deck
that doesn't allow the bolts

35:56.748 --> 35:58.041
<i>to lie flat.</i>

35:58.041 --> 35:59.376
When you see it loaded in here,

35:59.376 --> 36:01.252
it's already
sticking out there.

36:01.252 --> 36:03.671
When you compensate for that,
I'm not able to truly aim

36:03.671 --> 36:05.256
for the center.

36:05.256 --> 36:07.341
It looks like today
the deers get to live.

36:07.341 --> 36:10.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:10.510 --> 36:12.595
- All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the strength test.

36:12.595 --> 36:14.013
Now, to test the
strength of your bows

36:14.013 --> 36:15.765
as well as the strength
of your bolts,

36:15.765 --> 36:18.559
I'll be firing through these
two sheets of tempered glass

36:18.559 --> 36:20.227
at that X on the back wall.

36:20.227 --> 36:22.813
What we want to see is
a good flat trajectory

36:22.813 --> 36:24.731
and that bolt
busting through that glass,

36:24.731 --> 36:26.608
hitting as close
to that X as we can.

36:26.608 --> 36:29.068
Glass may be brittle,
but it's also incredibly hard.

36:29.068 --> 36:30.486
Even though your bolts can

36:30.486 --> 36:32.113
and probably will break
these panes,

36:32.113 --> 36:34.031
this test is
all about what the glass does

36:34.031 --> 36:35.450
to the tips of your bolts

36:35.450 --> 36:37.242
and not what your bolts
do to the glass.

36:37.242 --> 36:39.202
JD, you're up. You ready?
- Yep.

36:39.202 --> 36:42.205
<i>I hope my choice not to harden</i>
<i>these tips too much</i>

36:42.205 --> 36:44.416
doesn't, you know,
send me home.

36:44.416 --> 36:51.213
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:59.804 --> 37:01.681
[bolt clanging]
[clicks tongue]

37:01.681 --> 37:04.057
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:04.057 --> 37:06.101
- All right, JD,
you are one bolt down

37:06.101 --> 37:08.395
and two pieces
of glass still standing.

37:08.395 --> 37:15.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:16.694 --> 37:18.946
[bolt clanging]
- [scoffs]

37:18.946 --> 37:21.823
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:21.823 --> 37:24.493
- All right, so I've taken
my two shots at this target.

37:24.493 --> 37:26.161
You're one bolt down.

37:26.161 --> 37:27.954
You can see it kind of
flattened your tip off.

37:27.954 --> 37:29.331
Did you harden these tips?

37:29.331 --> 37:30.873
- They're tempered way down.

37:30.873 --> 37:32.208
- Oh, okay, you brought
them way back.

37:32.208 --> 37:35.920
Well, it draws well.
It fires nicely.

37:35.920 --> 37:38.797
It would have been nice
to see that tip, you know,

37:38.797 --> 37:40.173
be a little bit harder.

37:40.173 --> 37:41.466
But you did
a good job building this.

37:41.466 --> 37:42.759
- Thank you.
- All right.

37:42.759 --> 37:44.260
John-Francis, you're up.
Are you ready?

37:44.260 --> 37:45.428
- I guess so.

37:45.428 --> 37:52.309
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:07.531 --> 38:09.741
[chuckling]
Broke glass.

38:09.741 --> 38:12.118
- John-Francis,
see that tip?

38:12.118 --> 38:13.745
It's still there.

38:13.745 --> 38:16.330
That sharp tip hitting
the glass blew through it.

38:16.330 --> 38:18.582
As far as the construction
of your bow itself,

38:18.582 --> 38:19.959
it's very nice,
it's very solid.

38:19.959 --> 38:21.460
I like that a lot.

38:21.460 --> 38:23.462
You've got that
dropped deck to it.

38:23.462 --> 38:25.797
<i>But that should</i>
<i>probably happen</i>

38:25.797 --> 38:27.298
in front
of where the string is,

38:27.298 --> 38:29.551
because as that string
comes to the end,

38:29.551 --> 38:31.970
it's kind of loading the back
of that arrow

38:31.970 --> 38:33.887
and maybe lifting it up
somewhat.

38:33.887 --> 38:37.558
That might be why there's a lot
of odd trajectory going on.

38:37.558 --> 38:40.310
But I think you did
a fantastic job, and...

38:40.310 --> 38:41.812
definitely strong.

38:41.812 --> 38:43.521
Good job.
- Thank you.

38:43.521 --> 38:46.399
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:46.399 --> 38:49.318
- All right, bladesmiths,
now it's the sharpness test--

38:49.318 --> 38:51.611
the bubble bladder bust.

38:51.611 --> 38:54.573
Let's see if there's any
sharpness left with your bolts.

38:54.573 --> 38:55.740
JD, you're up first.
You ready?

38:55.740 --> 38:57.325
- Yep.

38:57.325 --> 38:59.047
<i>I'm definitely nervous.</i>

39:02.913 --> 39:05.249
<i>- We're basically</i>
<i>at the exact same spot.</i>

39:05.249 --> 39:06.834
It's all gonna come down
to this last test.

39:06.834 --> 39:10.920
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:15.091 --> 39:17.093
[chuckles]

39:17.093 --> 39:18.969
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:18.969 --> 39:22.055
- All right, JD, your crossbow
gave enough velocity

39:22.055 --> 39:25.183
for a sharp bolt to go through
the bladders and into the wall.

39:25.183 --> 39:27.351
It will cut.
- Thanks.

39:27.351 --> 39:28.936
- John-Francis, you're up.
Ready?

39:28.936 --> 39:30.438
- Ready.
- Let's do this.

39:30.438 --> 39:37.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:43.199 --> 39:44.951
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:44.951 --> 39:48.162
- All right, John-Francis,
your bolt went straight

39:48.162 --> 39:50.623
all the way through
and into the wall.

39:50.623 --> 39:54.126
So, for this test, sir,
your weapon will cut.

39:54.126 --> 39:56.169
Good job.
- Thank you very much.

39:56.169 --> 39:58.838
The kill test--
my weapon failed.

39:58.838 --> 40:01.132
In the strength test,
JD's weapon failed.

40:01.132 --> 40:03.051
Seems like it's staying close
even to the end.

40:03.051 --> 40:04.926
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:04.926 --> 40:07.054
- JD, John-Francis,
we sent you home,

40:07.054 --> 40:08.680
and we had you do something

40:08.680 --> 40:10.599
we've never had
anybody do before,

40:10.599 --> 40:13.476
and you both created
lethal works of art.

40:13.476 --> 40:17.021
And that's exactly why this
decision was so hard.

40:17.021 --> 40:19.148
But a decision has been made.

40:19.148 --> 40:21.316
And only one of you can be
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

40:21.316 --> 40:22.817
And that champion is...

40:22.817 --> 40:27.238
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:27.238 --> 40:29.282
JD.

40:29.282 --> 40:31.241
Congratulations, you're the
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:31.241 --> 40:33.869
John-Francis,
unfortunately, your crossbow

40:33.869 --> 40:36.163
did not make the cut.

40:36.163 --> 40:38.999
- John-Francis,
you have a powerful crossbow.

40:38.999 --> 40:42.043
But your design kept launching
those bolts differently,

40:42.043 --> 40:43.920
<i>therefore not making</i>
<i>it very accurate.</i>

40:43.920 --> 40:45.546
And for that reason,
we're sending you home.

40:45.546 --> 40:47.340
- I understand.

40:47.340 --> 40:49.132
- John-Francis, I'm gonna have
to ask you

40:49.132 --> 40:50.801
to please surrender
your crossbow.

40:50.801 --> 40:52.678
♪ ♪

40:52.678 --> 40:55.138
<i>- Obviously I'm disappointed,</i>
<i>but his was</i>

40:55.138 --> 40:56.515
<i>definitely more accurate,</i>
<i>and that is something</i>

40:56.515 --> 40:58.349
that's important
to have for a crossbow.

40:58.349 --> 41:00.643
I definitely gained a sense
of confidence in my skills

41:00.643 --> 41:03.104
and was able to have
a good time along the way.

41:03.104 --> 41:06.856
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:06.856 --> 41:08.525
- JD, congratulations.

41:08.525 --> 41:10.318
You are our new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:10.318 --> 41:13.988
and that is a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

41:13.988 --> 41:16.073
How you feeling?
- [chuckles] Pretty good.

41:16.073 --> 41:17.700
[laughter]
- Man of few words.

41:17.700 --> 41:20.369
Please present
your weapon to the judges.

41:20.369 --> 41:24.122
- I didn't expect to win,
but I definitely proved

41:24.122 --> 41:25.707
<i>what I came here to prove.</i>

41:25.707 --> 41:28.292
I'm the new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:28.292 --> 41:30.044
and I hate crossbows.

41:30.044 --> 41:32.046
I hate them.
[chuckles]

41:32.046 --> 41:38.176
<i>♪ ♪</i>
